<dl id="n53097aj"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53097aj">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53097aj"> 97(aj)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> tongueopener, <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53097aj"><li>FW 345.27 </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/lexmd.htm#n53097aj">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/l39md.htm#n53097aj">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53097aj">MS BL 47480-84v</ms> </li><li>JJA 55:160 <a name="mdd5" href="../../FF/fdra/mda.htm#mdd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/md/mdd5.htm#n53097aj">Draft: II.3&sect;4.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;Do you think we could do anything with one of those instruments for opening tongues?&rdquo; hazarded the Staff Captain, when the silence had become oppressive and the outbursts of fire extinguished. <p>&ldquo;We might try.&rdquo; The signalling officer was doubtful, but sallied forth, and after some delay returned with one. &ldquo;Where shall we start?&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;Any old place.&rdquo; The Staff Captain gripped the implement and stepped manfully forward. &ldquo;We&apos;re going to try something else, sir&mdash;a <mark>tongue-opener</mark>.&rdquo;</p> <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> <p>To emerge into the light of two candles and an electric torch with a bit of one ear and half a face deficient, and realise that the man responsible for it is offering you your uppers in three parts and some fragments, is a situation too dreadful to contemplate.</p> <small> H.C. McNeile (&ldquo;Sapper&rdquo;) <a name="SJW" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SJW"><cite title="source">John Walters</cite></a> (1927) The Man-Trap, 136-8</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
